post_text:
There are only 15 days left to meet the September 30 deadline to complete the 2020 Census.

In 2010, Mississippi‚Äôs Census completion rate was 61.3%, and the state lost a congressional seat and millions in federal money.

As of today, Mississippi‚Äôs completion rate is 59.3%. Our state risks losing millions in federal funds if all our citizens are not counted.

About the 2020 Census:

It‚Äôs quick and easy. The 2020 Census questionnaire will take about 10 minutes to complete. It‚Äôs safe, secure, and confidential. Your information and privacy are protected. Your response helps to direct billions of dollars in federal funds to local communities for schools, roads, and other public services. Results from the 2020 Census will be used to determine the number of seats each state has in Congress and your political representation at all levels of government. https://my2020census.gov/ #RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence

post_text: Social distancing means keeping a safe space between yourself and other people. To practice social distancing, stay at least 6 feet (about 2 arms' length) from other people who are not from your household in both indoor and outdoor spaces.
text: Social distancing means keeping a safe space between yourself and other people. To practice social distancing, stay at least 6 feet (about 2 arms' length) from other people who are not from your household in both indoor and outdoor spaces.

post_text:
What is the difference between a CLOSE contact and a GROUP contact for COVID-19?

A close contact is defined as any individual who was within 6 feet of an infected person for at least 15 minutes starting from 2 days before illness onset (or, for asymptomatic patients, 2 days prior to positive test) until the time the patient is isolated. Close contacts MUST QUARANTINE for 14 days. You should monitor for symptoms for 14 days after the last exposure to the infected person. Testing is recommended but a negative test will not negate the 14 day quarantine period.

A group contact is defined as a contact within a school or larger group, classroom or activity but not within 6 feet for more than 15 minutes from the infected person.

Group contacts DO NOT HAVE TO QUARANTINE . It is recommended that you monitor for symptoms and do temperature checks at least 2x daily for 14 days after the last exposure to the infected person.
#RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence #MASKup

Richland Upper Elementary fb
August 15 at 2:41 PM ¬∑

RUES and RES would like to send a HUGE shoutout to International Paper in Richland, MS, for providing us with our Protective Desk Shields. Our teachers, students, and parents, are very appreciative of your collaboration with us during these uncharted times. It comforts us to know we will begin the 20-21 school year more protected because of the people in the GREAT Richland Community. Mr. Bill and Mr. Art even hand delivered the boards to each teacher‚Äôs classroom. Our teachers immediately began assembling the shields along with volunteers from International Paper (all social distancing and masks protocols were followed)! It‚Äôs a great YEAR to be a RANGER and a part of the BEST school district, RCSD!

#adventureawaits
#groundedandgrowing

Social distancing is one of the best tools to avoid being exposed to COVID-19. To help slow the spread of the virus, keep these key times in mind for when to use social distancing

Inside your home if someone is sick
Outside your home when around people who are not in your household
If you are at increased risk for severe illness from COVID-19
If maintaining social distancing will be difficult, wear a mask when around others, including when you must go out in public. Learn more: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/social-distancing.html

post_text:
The CDC & Prevention is working to help keep you & your community safe from the threat of COVID-19. Take the following everyday steps to help avoid the spread of all respiratory viruses:

Wash your hands often with soap & water for at least 20 seconds.

Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, throw the tissue away, & then wash your hands.

Avoid touching your eyes, nose, & mouth.

Clean & disinfect frequently touched objects or surfaces such as remote controls & doorknobs.

Avoid close contact with people who are sick.

Stay home if you are sick. Call your doctor if you develop fever, cough, or difficulty breathing.

For more tips, visit www.cdc.gov.
#RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence Bring Everyone‚Äôs Strengths Together - BEST

Summer is a great time to read. The Mississippi Department of Education (MDE) has revamped its Strong Readers website, http://ow.ly/Zpt730qMylr, to help families assist their children with building their reading skills.

The site is organized by grade level, from kindergarten through grade 5. It includes strategies for developing strong reader habits and a series of activities to practice the five components of reading. Those include working with sounds, phonics, fluency, vocabulary and comprehension.
Also included are tools for families to find books that match their child‚Äôs grade band and a free, online library. http://ow.ly/AEuh30qMyls g2b #traditionofexcellence

The Mississippi State Department of Health (MSDH) is urging parents to act now & schedule their child‚Äôs age-appropriate immunizations before summer is over. Mississippi state law requires children to be immunized against childhood diseases to enter public or private school, Head Start or daycare.

Make an appointment at your county health department clinic to bring your child in for their immunizations. A list of county health department locations along with times and days the clinics are open can be found at www.HealthyMS.com/locations.

Parents should bring the child‚Äôs social security card & insurance card if available. Parents & children over 2 must wear a mask when entering the county health department clinic. #RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence

post_text:
Summer is a great time to read. The Mississippi Department of Education (MDE) has revamped its Strong Readers website, http://ow.ly/Zpt730qMylr, to help families assist their children with building their reading skills.

The site is organized by grade level, from kindergarten through grade 5. It includes strategies for developing strong reader habits and a series of activities to practice the five components of reading. Those include working with sounds, phonics, fluency, vocabulary and comprehension.

Also included are tools for families to find books that match their child‚Äôs grade band and a free, online library.
#RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence

post_text: Sometimes heroes don't always wear capes. RCSD has a district full of heroes. This summer our child nutrition department and volunteers from schools and various departments throughout the district worked during school closures due to COVID-19, and have continued to work to feed our students through the month of June. We applaud their hard work and dedication to our communities. These dedicated people have prepared and served more than 100,000 meals! Today, June 29th our Grab & Go will come to an end. We salute these heroes and can't thank them enough for their dedication to our RCSD families. Grab and Go will be open today from 10:30 am - 12:30 pm. #RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence

The Mississippi State Department of Health (MSDH) is urging parents to act now & schedule their child‚Äôs age-appropriate immunizations before summer is over. Mississippi state law requires children to be immunized against childhood diseases to enter public or private school, Head Start or daycare.

Make an appointment at your county health department clinic to bring your child in for their immunizations. A list of county health department locations along with times and days the clinics are open can be found at www.HealthyMS.com/locations.

Parents should bring the child‚Äôs social security card & insurance card if available. Parents & children over 2 must wear a mask when entering the county health department clinic. #RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence

post_text:
Registration for incoming Kindergarten students to register for this FREE summer learning experience ends soon. Please register TODAY!

Registration ends June 8th: Here is the link on the MDE website:
http://ow.ly/uRyU50zZb4d

The Audacious grant that Waterford was awarded, has notified us about an amazing opportunity. We have been allotted 2500 seats for at risk, low income students that have lost learning due to COVID 19. Those that qualify will receive a computer, internet access and a dedicated support person. Along with access to Waterford's UPSTART in-home Kindergarten readiness program that gives children a fun start in reading, math and science (with a focus on reading) in just 25 minutes a day.

The program is June through August so it is a quick turnaround. The information is available in both English and Spanish.

Summer is a great time to read. The Mississippi Department of Education (MDE) has revamped its Strong Readers website, http://ow.ly/Zpt730qMylr, to help families assist their children with building their reading skills.

The site is organized by grade level, from kindergarten through grade 5. It includes strategies for developing strong reader habits and a series of activities to practice the five components of reading. Those include working with sounds, phonics, fluency, vocabulary and comprehension.

Also included are tools for families to find books that match their child‚Äôs grade band and a free, online library. http://ow.ly/AEuh30qMyls g2b #traditionofexcellence

post_text:
The CDC & Prevention is working to help keep you & your community safe from the threat of COVID-19. Take the following everyday steps to help avoid the spread of all respiratory viruses:

Wash your hands often with soap & water for at least 20 seconds.

Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, throw the tissue away, & then wash your hands.

Avoid touching your eyes, nose, & mouth.

Clean & disinfect frequently touched objects or surfaces such as remote controls & doorknobs.

Avoid close contact with people who are sick.

Stay home if you are sick. Call your doctor if you develop fever, cough, or difficulty breathing.

For more tips, visit www.cdc.gov.
#RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence Bring Everyone's Strengths Together - BEST

Digital Access Surveys for Families: Please complete by May 11th

As school closures continue and as the state develops plans to direct resources to the areas of greatest need, the MDE has prepared a brief survey for districts to circulate to families. The survey focuses on devices at home, home internet access, and the quality/reliability of that connection.
Aggregated results from districts will be shared with the governor‚Äôs office for planning purposes. Because of the critical nature of these questions ‚Äì and how the results will shape state policy to address the internet connectivity challenges across the state ‚Äì It is important that families complete the survey.
Again, please complete by May 11. #RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence Bring Everyone‚Äôs Strengths Together - BEST

http://ow.ly/vYMl50ztGxK
or visit www.rcsd.ms/DigitalAccess

Digital Access Surveys for Families: Please complete by May 11th

As school closures continue and as the state develops plans to direct resources to the areas of greatest need, the MDE has prepared a brief survey for districts to circulate to families. The survey focuses on devices at home, home internet access, and the quality/reliability of that connection.
Aggregated results from districts will be shared with the governor‚Äôs office for planning purposes. Because of the critical nature of these questions ‚Äì and how the results will shape state policy to address the internet connectivity challenges across the state ‚Äì It is important that families complete the survey.

The focus for April is Alcohol Awareness. Know the rsks of Underage Drinking Today -
* Most underage drinking is in the form of binge drinking.
* Combination of alcohol & prescription medicines are especially dangerous
* 50% of college students' sexual assaults are associated with alcohol use by perpetrator, victim, or both
* Social media creates a "permanent record" of poor decisions

post_text:
There is a FAKE letter circulating across social media stating that Rankin County School District has made the decision to close schools for the remainder of the 2019/2020 school year and that each student will be retained, meaning that each student will repeat the current grade he/she is enrolled. This is NOT TRUE. Rankin County School District has not made any further decisions. We continue to stay in close contact with and follow the guidance from the Mississippi State Department of Health, the Mississippi Department of Education, and the Governor. We will keep you updated as decisions are made.

Governor Tate Reeves posted on his Facebook page that there will be a press conference at 3:30 pm today. Please check your local news or follow him on his Facebook page where it will be live streamed.
#RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence

Rankin County School District will be providing FREE Grab and Go meals beginning Wednesday, April 1st at 4 new locations. Meals will be available M-F from 10:30 am ‚Äì 12:30 pm. post_text:
FROM THE NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE of JACKSON: ATTENTION 4th, 5th, and 6th GRADERS!

With all of us learning and working from home, the National Hurricane Center is happy to announce that they will be hosting a series of #HurricanesAtHome webinars for 4th, 5th, and 6th graders who live in states and territories along the U.S. Gulf and Atlantic coasts over the next several weeks! The webinars will focus on the job of a meteorologist, the weather hazards that come with hurricanes, and how meteorologists get you the weather information you need before a storm.

Please click on this link for more information on registering and to find the dates for where you live:

https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/pdf/Hurricane_at_Home.pdf

Future information will be posted on Facebook and on NHC‚Äôs @NWSNHC and @NHC_Atlantic Twitter feeds. We‚Äôre looking forward to talking with you!

With all of us learning and working from home, the National Hurricane Center is happy to announce that they will be hosting a series of #HurricanesAtHome webinars for 4th, 5th, and 6th graders who live in states and territories along the U.S. Gulf and Atlantic coasts over the next several weeks! The webinars will focus on the job of a meteorologist, the weather hazards that come with hurricanes, and how meteorologists get you the weather information you need before a storm.

Please click on this link for more information on registering and to find the dates for where you live:

Future information will be posted on Facebook and on NHC‚Äôs @NWSNHC and @NHC_Atlantic Twitter feeds. We‚Äôre looking forward to talking with you!

post_text: CORONAVIRUS (COVID-19) - [updated 3/15/20 5:35pm] The Rankin County School District has extended Spring Break for two weeks. All schools [and Frontiers] will be closed Monday, March 16 through Friday, March 27 per the recommendation of Governor Tate Reeves. As a result, March's tuition will be prorated to $10 per school day in March (regardless of your child's attendance on these days, as such applies to general tuition). The remainder of March's tuition will be credited towards tuition when we return. We will not "bank draft" tuition until further notice. For more information visit our website at http://ow.ly/jqlO50yMsnP

post_text: One of the 2020 Clarion Ledger baseball Dandy Dozen athletes happens to be RCSD's very own Kellum Clark from Brandon High School. Through 32 games, he batted an even .500. He led the Bulldogs with 41 hits, 46 runs scored, 40 RBIs and 10 home runs. He also tallied a team-high 42 walks and a .986 fielding percentage, making just two errors on 143 total chances. He went 3-1 on the mound with a 3.36 ERA. He has signed with Mississippi State. #RCSDg2b #traditionofexcellence
